    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A *list comprehension* versus a *generator*, you say? A heartache! A list comprehension, like a pissed-off goblin militia, tries to build the *entire* resulting list in memory all at once, consuming RAM like a particularly greedy goblin hoard. A generator, however, acts more like a tiny, sneaky goblin popping out of a rock—it yields one item at a time *only when requested*, keeping your memory footprint incredibly low. For those massive CSV files, you absolutely want the generator approach; it's the lean, hungry goblin of Python memory management.\n\nTo illustrate, with a list comprehension, if you have a billion rows, pandas tries to load all billion items into RAM instantly. Imagine trying to stuff a million tiny, grubby goblins into one tiny backpack—it just pops open and spills everywhere, causing that glorious `MemoryError`! The memory usage of a list comprehension scales with the *entire* output size, which is why it chokes on your big CSV, just like trying to fit all the lumpy, oversized goblin loot into a single pouch.\n\nGenerators, on the other hand, are lazy; they are *iterators*. Instead of calculating everything upfront, they calculate the next value",
